syndrome","Coeliac disease","Giardiasis","Tropical sprue","Whipple disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological features shown are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E, including villous atrophy, crypt hyperplasia, and increased intraepithelial lymphocytes. These changes occur due to gluten-triggered immune response in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial overgrowth syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows less severe villous changes and prominent inflammatory infiltrates. \u003Cstrong\u003ETropical sprue\u003C/strong\u003E can show similar villous changes but is geographically restricted and responds to antibiotics and folate. \u003Cstrong\u003EWhipple disease\u003C/strong\u003E shows periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) positive macrophages in the lamina propria. \u003Cstrong\u003EGiardiasis\u003C/strong\u003E shows relatively preserved villous architecture with parasitic organisms visible in the lumen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coeliac disease shows characteristic histological features including villous atrophy, crypt hyperplasia, and increased intraepithelial lymphocytes.","Coeliac disease is an immune-mediated enteropathy triggered by gluten exposure in genetically susceptible individuals."],"references":["Lebwohl B, Rubio-Tapia A. Epidemiology, Presentation, and Diagnosis of Celiac Disease. Gastroenterology. 2021 Jan;160(1):63-75. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2020.06.098. Epub 2020 Sep 18. PMID: 32950520.","Posner EB, Haseeb M. Celiac Disease. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722929.","\u0022Coeliac path\u0022 by ToNToNi is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coeliac_path.jpg","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u00